In addition, degradation of magnesium in an aqueous solution and the subsequent formation of hexagonal platelet-like magnesium hydroxide structures were observed in the presence of chlorides (Fig. 5
                     ). Ions of chloride which are rapidly absorbed on the magnesium surface facilitate a faster degradation of magnesium compared to the anodic dissolution of magnesium in an aqueous solution without chlorides (Fig. 6
                     ) and speed up the transformation of magnesium to brucite.
